   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3181_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>The Little Orchard</addrLine>
                  <!--Check how to mark up printed design around address-->
                  <addrLine>Shoreham</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Kent</addrLine>
               </address>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m01"/>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m02"/>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1914-11-25">No 25.14</date>
               </dateline>

               <salute>My dear friend –</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>The <ref target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">volume of <choice><abbr>y<hi
                           rend="superscript">r</hi></abbr>
                     <expan>your</expan></choice>. Poems</ref> has reached me safely – &amp; I send
                  <hi rend="underline">many</hi> thanks. Some day you must write my name in it,
               please, &amp; I shall feel then that it really is <hi rend="underline">from</hi>
               you.</p>
            <p> I have read a great many poems, &amp; see that there is a great deal that is
               beautiful in the book. <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3181_2.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">Very</hi> especially do I like the one to <persName
                  ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Florence</persName> - There are such lovely lines in that
               -! (The 2<hi rend="superscript">nd</hi> &amp; 3<hi rend="superscript">rd</hi> stanzas
               - &amp; the "large luminous living eyes–") I hope she likes that poem <hi
                  rend="underline">very</hi> much herself?</p>
            <p> I have not read all yet, but among things that struck me, or in some way appealed to
               me, are: "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">In the Moonlight</ref>":
                  "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">Before &amp; after
                  Summer</ref>": (which <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3181_3.jpg"/> I <hi
                  rend="underline">already</hi> knew &amp; liked –) "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">When I set out for
               Lyonnesse</ref>"–: (a <hi rend="underline">lovely</hi> lyric that,)–: / "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">Her Secret</ref>"-: "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">Beeny Cliff</ref>"- "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">The Death of Regret</ref>–" (which
               is wonderfully true, I am afraid!) &amp; "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance">The Workbox</ref>"– –</p>
            <p>I saw very pleasant criticism of the "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1904-1908_TheDynasts"
                  >Dynasts</ref>", so hope the production will be of much interest to you &amp;
                  <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Florence</persName>. <persName
                  ref="#ps:HarleyGranvilleBarker"><choice><abbr>G.</abbr>
                     <expan>Granville</expan></choice> Barker</persName> seems to have done his
               share well? – </p>
            <p>Please thank <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy"><choice><abbr>F.</abbr>
                     <expan>Florence</expan></choice></persName> for her very nice letter. I am
               sorry <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3181_4.jpg"/> that you think <name>"Britannia"
                  Milner</name>
               <choice><abbr>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>would</expan></choice> be too noisy for you! But perhaps <hi
                  rend="underline">2</hi> dogs racing <unclear>around</unclear>
               <choice><abbr>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>would</expan></choice> be a somewhat disturbing influence. I feel glad,
               however, that you have got Wessex, &amp; that the birds are <hi rend="underline"
                  >safe</hi> in <choice><abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</abbr>
                  <expan>your</expan></choice> garden. </p>
            <p>To return to the poems – I am glad you have included the <ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1914_MenWhoMarchAway">Song of the Soldiers</ref>.</p>
            <p>I thought <persName ref="#ps:EdmundGosse">Mr Gosse</persName>'s poem "To our Dead" –
               I think it was called, really fine, didn't you?</p>

            <pb n="5" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3181_5.jpg"/>
            <p xml:id="h3181a" corresp="#m01" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">My best love to
                  <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy"/>Florence. I hope she is well in this rather
               trying wet &amp; windy weather.</p>
            <closer xml:id="h3181b" corresp="#m02" style="transform:rotateZ(-90deg)">
               <salute><choice>
                     <abbr>yr</abbr>
                     <expan>your</expan>
                  </choice>
                  <choice>
                     <abbr>aff.</abbr>
                     <expan>affectionate</expan>
                  </choice>friend</salute>
               <signed>FH</signed>
            </closer>


